1.2 The Question

Questions 1-5 involve data from a randomized controlled trial compares four potential treatments for the repair of a valve. You will find a copy of the data in the dat01.csv file. The data set includes a variable called treat which contains the values 0, 1, 2, 3, and which needs to be recoded as a factor in R. Provide the code to import the dat01.csv file into a tibble called dat01 in R, and then create a factor within dat01 named treatment that has the following properties:

  1. treat = 0 refers to treatment = UC
  2. treat = 1 is captured as treatment = A1
  3. treat = 2 refers to treatment = A2
  4. treat = 3 refers to treatment = B
  5. the factor treatment is ordered A1, A2, B, UC.

You will know you have completed the task successfully when you obtain the following output:

dat01 %>% count(treatment)
# A tibble: 4 x 2
  treatment     n
  <fct>     <int>
1 A1           30
2 A2           30
3 B            30
4 UC           30

1.3 Answer 1 (5 points)

dat01 <- read.csv("dat01.csv") %>% tbl_df %>%
    mutate(treatment = fct_recode(factor(treat),
                                  A1 = "1", A2 = "2",
                                  B = "3", UC = "0"),
           treatment = fct_relevel(treatment, "A1", "A2", "B"))

2 Question 2

2.1 The Target Plot for Question 2

plot(TukeyHSD(
    aov(time_to_repair ~ treatment, data = dat01)), 
    las = 1)

2.2 The question

Question 2 involves the results of a randomized controlled trial comparing four potential treatments for the repair of a valve, which in question 1 you labeled as A1, A2, B and UC. The outcome of interest is time_to_repair = survival time before another repair of the same valve is required, which we’d like to be as large as possible. A1 and A2 are two versions of the “A” approach, “B” is a separate approach, and “UC” describes the standard approach (or “usual care”.) Your job is to use the data provided to you to produce the Target Plot shown above, which describes the results of Tukey’s HSD comparison, with a 95% confidence level. Your response should include the code to produce the Tukey HSD plot, working from the data frame you developed in Question 1. Thus, your response to Question 2 can be accomplished in a single line of R code. Note: to get the labels to show up on the y axis in this fashion rather than flipped 90 degrees, you’ll have to add the command las = 1 to your plot.

2.3 Answer 2 (5 points)

plot(TukeyHSD(aov(time_to_repair ~ treatment, data = dat01)), las = 1)

accomplishes the task.

3 Question 3

3.1 The question

Refer to the Target Plot from Question 2 and describe, in complete English sentences, the pairwise comparisons of the four potential treatments. What conclusions can you draw, in terms of statistical significance? Don’t forget to clearly indicate for each comparison whether one treatment appears to perform better or worse than another in terms of time to repair.

3.2 Answer 3 (10 points)

At a 5% family-wise significance level:

  • The mean time to repair for approaches B and A2 looks significantly better (longer) than A1 and also significantly better than Usual Care.
  • The mean time to repair for approaches B and A2 do not appear to be statistically significantly different. Nor do approaches A1 and Usual Care.

The dat04.csv data file specifies the subjects (that we have been studying in Questions 1-3) as well as their temperature (High or Low) at the time of the valve repair. I merged those data with the data in my dat01 data frame to produce the plot above. In a few sentences, describe what this plot tells you about the relationships between time to repair and the treatment received and the temperature. In particular, what does this plot tell you about how to fit an analysis of variance model?

4.2 Answer 4 (5 points)

Because the lines are nowhere near parallel that join the group means by temperature, the plot tells you that there is a meaningful interaction between temperature and treatment on time to repair, and so our ANOVA should include that interaction term.

6 Question 6

The dat06.csv data set contains information on 800 observations of an outcome variable, y, and nine predictors, labeled x1 through x9, plus a sample variable, which takes the value “development” for 600 observations and the value “testing” for the remaining 200 observations.

The four plots and the table below were obtained by running a “best subsets” procedure to identify models from the complete set of available predictors (the xs) to predict y, but including only the data in dat06 in the “development” sample.

set.seed(43216)
x1 <- rnorm(800, mean = 200, sd = 50)
x2 <- rnorm(800, mean = 200, sd = 50) + 3*(x1 - 600)/7
x3 <- rnorm(800, mean = 20, sd = 5)
x4 <- rnorm(800, mean = 30, sd = 5)
x5 <- rpois(800, lambda = 5)
x6 <- rpois(800, lambda = 12)
x7 <- rbernoulli(800, p = 0.4)
x8 <- rnorm(800, mean = 20, sd = 4)
x9 <- rnorm(800, mean = 100, sd = 25)
err <- rnorm(800, mean = 0, sd = 24)
y <- 5*(x1-200)/50 - 2*(x2-200)/50 + 6*(x6-12)/12 - 4*(x9-100)/25 + 4*x7 + err
sample <- c(rep("development", 600), rep("testing", 200))

dat06 <- data_frame(subject = 1:800,
                    y, x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, x7, x8, x9, sample)

write_csv(dat06, "dat06.csv")

rm(x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, x7, x8, x9, err, y, sample)

preds <- with(dat06_dev, 
              cbind(x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, x7, x8, x9))
set <- regsubsets(preds, dat06_dev$y, nvmax = 10)
rs <- summary(set)
rs$aic.c <- 600*log(rs$rss / 600) + 2*(2:10) +

best_mods_1 <- data_frame(

7 Question 7

Fit the models suggested by each of the four plots within the “development” sample in Question 6, then use those models to make predictions for every value in the “testing” sample. Compare the four models in terms of their root mean squared prediction error and their mean absolute prediction error. Write a sentence or two to explain the results and pick a “winning” model.

7.1 Answer 7 (15 points)

First, we fit the four models in the development sample:

m03 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x9, data = dat06_dev)
m04 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x4 + x9, data = dat06_dev)
m05 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x4 + x6 + x9, data = dat06_dev)
m06 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x4 + x6 + x9, data = dat06_dev)

Next, we use each model to predict the cases in the testing sample, and save the predictions and errors.

pred03 <- predict(m03, newdata = dat06_test)
errors03 <- dat06_test$y - pred03

pred04 <- predict(m04, newdata = dat06_test)
errors04 <- dat06_test$y - pred04

pred05 <- predict(m05, newdata = dat06_test)
errors05 <- dat06_test$y - pred05

pred06 <- predict(m06, newdata = dat06_test)
errors06 <- dat06_test$y - pred06

Then, we calculate and compare the root mean squared errors and the mean absolute errors from each model.

rmse03 <- sqrt(mean(errors03^2))
mae03 <- mean(abs(errors03))

rmse04 <- sqrt(mean(errors04^2))
mae04 <- mean(abs(errors04))

rmse05 <- sqrt(mean(errors05^2))
mae05 <- mean(abs(errors05))

rmse06 <- sqrt(mean(errors06^2))
mae06 <- mean(abs(errors06))

Here are the results:

Model RMSE MAE
3 24.09 18.81
4 24.15 18.86
5 24.11 18.82
6 24.03 18.69

The results are pretty similar across the four models, but the model with 6 predictors (including the intercept) has slightly lower RMSE and mean absolute error, so it “wins.” That’s the model with x1, x2, x4, x6 and x9.

9 Question 9

Assess the regression assumptions of the model that you fit in Question 8. Show the usual four residual and diagnostic plots of the regression model after fitting it to the entire sample of 800 observations, and interpret the results.

9.1 Answer 9 (10 points)

To answer this, I’ll build the lm version of the model.

model_q9 <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x4 + x6 + x9, data = dat06)

Here is the set of four residual plots.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model_q9)

par(mfrow = c(1,1))

I see no problems with assumption violations in this model.

  • The residuals vs. fitted values looks like a random scatter, a “fuzzy football” with no apparent curve or fan shape.
  • The residuals appear well-modeled by a Normal distribution in the Q-Q plot. There’s not much deviation from the diagonal line.
  • The scale-location plot shows no particular signs of heteroscedasticity, as the square root of the standardized residuals seems to be distributed around a constant mean as we move from low to high fitted values.
  • Finally, the residuals vs. leverage plot shows no particularly influential or highly-leveregaed points, nor do we see any residuals that are substantially larger than we’d expect with 800 observations.

11.1 Answer 11 (10 points, 5 points for each part)

11.1.1 Part 11a (5 points)

A change in size from 100.5 to 135.5 is associated with an estimated 37% increase in odds of a good outcome, holding treatment and ses_group constant. The 95% confidence interval (0.91, 2.05) for the odds ratio, since it contains 1, indicates no statistically significant difference in those odds can be attributed to this size effect.

11.1.2 Part 11b (5 points)

Because size is a quantitative variable, and in the lrm output, the effect size is described for a difference between a size at the 25th percentile (100.5) and a size at the 75th percentile (135.5), so we see the effect on the odds ratio for a good outcome of a 35-unit change in size holding the other predictors constant. In question 10’s output, built using lm, we instead saw the effect on the odds ratio for a good outcome of a 1-unit change in size holding the other predictors constant.

12 Question 12

Using the data from Question 10, obtain a Spearman \(\rho^2\) plot and use it to identify a good way to add a single additional non-linear term to this model (you may spend only a single additional degree of freedom). What addition would you make?

12.1 Answer 12 (5 points)

Here is the Spearman \(\rho^2\) plot.

plot(spearman2(goodoutcome ~ size + treatment + 
                   catg(ses_group), data = dat10))

Treatment is the most promising variable, and is binary. Size is next, which is quantitative, so it looks like adding a treatment-size interaction is the most promising way to spend a single additional degree of freedom.

14 Question 14

Using the data from Question 10, fit the model you specified in Question 12 (including the non-linear term), while also accounting for missing data using multiple imputation. Set your seed to be 432432, and impute the predictors that need imputation using all available observations on all available variables.

Specify the code you used to fit your imputation model and your outcome model, specify the resulting fitted outcome model in terms of odds ratio estimates and a nomogram, and then write a few English sentences describing how the addition of imputation and a non-linear term changes (or doesn’t change) the conclusions from what we saw in the m1 model in Questions 10 and 11.

14.1 Answer 14 (15 points)

Here is the imputation model that I fit. I chose parameters here that seemed popular among the people doing the assignment, probably because it mirrors the approach in Chapter 15 of the Course Notes.

d <- datadist(dat10)
options(datadist = "d")

imp_14 <- aregImpute(~ goodoutcome + size + 
                         catg(treatment) + catg(ses_group), 
                     nk = c(0, 3), 
                     tlinear = TRUE, data = dat10, B = 10,
                     n.impute = 20, pr = FALSE)

Now, let’s fit the actual logistic regression model, with multiple imputation.

d <- datadist(dat10)
options(datadist = "d")

(mod14 <- fit.mult.impute(goodoutcome ~ 
                             size * catg(treatment) + 
                             catg(ses_group), 
                         fitter = lrm, xtrans = imp_14,
                         data = dat10, x = TRUE, y = TRUE))

The treatment effect, which was borderline significant in the original model, is not quite significant in the ANOVA table for this model with imputation and an interaction term.

plot(anova(mod14))

Comparing this model with imputation to a full set of 250 observations and a product term to capture interaction to the model for 232 observations that we fit in Question 10-11, we see the following:

  • The model discrimination is a bit better in the model with imputation and the interaction term.
    • The C statistic for this model, with imputation and interaction, is 0.616, as compared to 0.608 for the original model.
    • The Nagelkerke R2 for this model is 0.051, a bit larger than the 0.045 for the original model.
  • But the interaction term, like the rest of the model, carries no statistical significance, and neither did any part of the previous model.
